        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="head">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Romana[e] historia[e] primus flos, et vigor: vnius alteriusq[ue] lectoris opinione.
                        Virescit vulnere virtus: adamantinum generosa[e] a[e]mulationis, pra[e]stantia[e]q[ue] fundamentum. 
                        Ni Carthago fuisset Roma[e] asperrima hostis; nunq[uam] Roma fuisset Orbis potentissima domina. 
                        Quò aduersa
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <location name="Rome"/>
                    <location name="Carthage"/>
                    <X-ref book_title="Unknown" language="LA" person="Aulus Furius Antias" text="Virescit vulnere virtus"/>
                </position>
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text> fortuna infestior, eò tandem prospera fortuna ingentior: vbi militat virtus indomita; palma[e] praeclara a[e]mula.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>The first flourishing and vigour of Roman history in the opinion of one or two readers.
                "Courage grows strong from a wound:" The solid basis of noble and extraordinary rivalry. Had Carthage not been Rome’s harshest enemy, 
                Rome would never have been the most powerful master of the world. The more troublesome the misfortune is, 
                the greater the luck in the end, when valour fights unbroken, as an excellent competitor for victory.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia anchor_text="legatos maiores natu" hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Honoratissima[e] Romanorum Legationes: ad Carthaginenses: Hispanos: Gallos. Nullus historicus tam vividè legatu[m] agit, 
                        aut Iurisc[onsultus] quàm Liuius. hîc s[upr]a, i[nfr]a. Valdè conducit pragmatico, tales omnes legationes penitùs excutere.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Livy"/>
                    <location name="Rome"/>
                    <location name="Carthage"/>
                    <location name="Spain"/>
                    <location name="Gaul"/>
                    <internal_ref>
                        <target ref="PrincetonPA6452:00000039" text="s[upr]a"/>
                    </internal_ref>
                    <internal_ref text="i[nfr]a">
                        <target ref="PrincetonPA6452:00000680" text="[658]"/>
                        <target ref="PrincetonPA6452:00000681" text="[659]"/>
                        <target ref="PrincetonPA6452:00000759" text="[737]"/>
                    </internal_ref>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>The most honorable embassies of the Romans to the Carthaginians, Spaniards, Gauls. No historian discusses the 
                ambassador or jurist so lively as Livy does. [See] here above, below. It is very beneficial for the pragmatic fully to examine all 
                such embassies.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        directa belli denunciatio.
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>A straightforward declaration of war.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Politicum desidero, qui vtrunq[ue] adamantinum fundamentum altioribus radicibus figens, et optima pra[e]cepta optimis 
                        exemplis illustrans, Aristotelem ipsum Principiorum pondere; Machiauellum historiarum delectu superauerit. 
                        Mihi placeret, ibi incipere, vbi Machiauellus, Dana[e]usq[ue] desinunt: et posterioribus Romanorum consilijs, legibus, armis, 
                        iudicijs, magistratibus, negotijs, industrijs, imperijs, priora solerter corrigere, nauiterq[ue] extendere. Nec non alia superaddere, 
                        qua[e] in alijs florentissimis mundi imperijs, regnis, rebuspublicis eminentissima pra[e]celluerunt. Tum nihil in subtilissimis scholae 
                        doctoribus, aut profundissimis mundi pragmaticis inexcussum relinquere, aut inexploratum, vndè ipsis principijs aliquid accedat 
                        reformationis, aut incrementi.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Aristotle"/>
                    <person name="Machiavelli"/>
                    <person name="Lambert Daneau"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>I long for a politician who will surpass Aristotle himself in the weight of his principles and Machiavelli through the appeal 
                of his stories, securing each of them on a solid foundation with very long roots, and illuminating the best advice with the best examples.
                I would like to start at the point where Machiavelli and Daneau stop, and in the later councils of the Romans, their laws, arms, 
                judgments, magistrates, affairs, activities, orders, skilfully correct the previous [lessons] and diligently continue them. 
                And to add some other absolutely brilliant ones, that excelled in other very successful empires, kingdoms and republics in the world. 
                Furthermore to leave nothing unexamined or unexplored in the most sophisticated doctors of the schools, or in the most profound 
                pragmatics of the world, which may add some point of correction or improvement.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
